Introduction

On November 8th, the presidential election was coming to a close. While some students at UC Berkeley were eagerly encouraging their fellow students to vote for Hillary Clinton, other students did not feel the need to; how in the world could Trump be elected, they thought? Unfortunately, the student population of UC Berkeley was proven wrong, and presidential elect Trump beat out Clinton in what has turned out to be one of the most controversial presidential races in history.

Polls were made, and predictions were formed off of the culminated data. Hillary Clinton had a supposed 71.4% chance of winning. How could Data Science have let us down in this crucial time? Fortunately, the analytical journey doesn’t end here; by doing an analysis on the election data from the years 2004, 2008, 2010, 2012, and the current year (2016), we can see how the voters’ opinions have swayed throughout the years, and how the dynamically shifting atmosphere of the world has impacted the voters’ decisions.

In this project, we were able perform data scraping, a visual analysis, and create a predictive model using a Naive Bayes Classifier and a Classification Tree. By using a combination of ggplot, map creation, and supervised learning techniques, we were able to model our results, create predictors, and compare our predictions to the correct data sets.

1.2 - Extracting 2012 Election Data

Extracts the xml files for each state. We ignore Alaska as it doesn’t have an entry for it. We then use a series of XPATHs to extract data for each state. Done by Derrick, Vinitra, and Shanaaz

generateStateURL <- function (state) {
  return(paste("http://www.stat.berkeley.edu/users/nolan/data/voteProject/countyVotes2012/", state,".xml", sep = ""))
}
generateURLs2012 <- sapply(states, generateStateURL)
stateData2012 <- sapply(generateURLs2012, function(l) xmlParse(l))
stateRoots2012 <- sapply(stateData2012, function(state) xmlRoot(state))

# The county ids for 2012
countyNodeSet2012 <- sapply(stateRoots2012, function(root)getNodeSet(root, "//tbody[@id]"))

# get geogID
geoIDs2012 <- sapply(countyNodeSet2012, function(node) xmlSApply(node, xmlGetAttr, "id"))
stateNames2012 <- unlist(sapply(seq(length(states)), function(i) rep(states[[i]], length(geoIDs2012[[i]]))))
stateNames2012 <- sub("-", " ", stateNames2012)
geoIDs2012 <- sub("county", "", unlist(unname(geoIDs2012)))

# get county names
countyNames2012 <- sapply(stateRoots2012, function(root) xpathSApply(root, '//th[@class="results-county"]', xmlValue))
countyNames2012 <- unlist(unname(countyNames2012))
countyNames2012 <- tolower(sub(" 100.0% Reporting", "", countyNames2012))
countyNames2012 <- countyNames2012[!(countyNames2012 == "county")]

geoIDs2012 <- unlist(unname(geoIDs2012))

# The number of republican votes for 2012
repVoteCount2012 <- unlist(unname(sapply(stateRoots2012, function(root) xpathSApply(root, '//tr[@class="party-republican race-winner"]/td[@class="results-popular"] | //tr[@class="party-republican"]/td[@class="results-popular"]', xmlValue))))
repVoteCount2012 <- sub("^\\s+", "", repVoteCount2012)
repVoteCount2012 <- sub(",", "", repVoteCount2012)

# The number of democrat votes for 2012
demVoteCount2012 <- unlist(unname(sapply(stateRoots2012, function(root) xpathSApply(root, '//tr[@class="party-democrat race-winner"]/td[@class="results-popular"] | //tr[@class="party-democrat"]/td[@class="results-popular"]', xmlValue))))
demVoteCount2012 <- sub("^\\s+", "", demVoteCount2012)
demVoteCount2012 <- sub(",", "", demVoteCount2012)

#The percentage of rep votes for 2012
perRepVotes2012 <- unlist(unname(sapply(stateRoots2012, function(root) xpathSApply(root, '//tr[@class="party-republican race-winner"]/td[@class="results-percentage"] | //tr[@class="party-republican"]/td[@class="results-percentage"]', xmlValue))))

#The percentage of dem votes for 2012
perDemVotes2012 <- unlist(unname(sapply(stateRoots2012, function(root) xpathSApply(root, '//tr[@class="party-democrat race-winner"]/td[@class="results-percentage"] | //tr[@class="party-democrat"]/td[@class="results-percentage"]', xmlValue))))

df2012 <- data.frame(geoIDs2012, stateNames2012, repVoteCount2012, perRepVotes2012, demVoteCount2012, perDemVotes2012, countyNames2012)

Step 1.3 - Extracting 2008 Election Data

Extract sheets one by one from an online google sheet. Formats state names. Has a special condition for California and Maine since they are misformatted. Warning: this will take a while to run. Done by Allen.

stateNames <- "http://www.stat.berkeley.edu/users/nolan/data/voteProject/countyVotes2012/stateNames.txt"
capitalize <- function(state) {
  words <- strsplit(state, " ")[[1]]
  paste(toupper(substring(words, 1,1)), substring(words, 2), sep="", collapse=" ")
}
states <- read.table(stateNames, header = TRUE)[[1]]
states <- states[states != "district-of-columbia"] # There is no entry for D.C.
states <- gsub("-", " ", states) # Must format to sheet names

sourceURL2008 <- "https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1gLzjUFBk9gtAPfZ-bNZVfFC1zNhGkY_WI_VD_OXHUYI/edit#gid=0"
demVoteCount2008 <- c()
repVoteCount2008 <- c()
otherCount2008 <- c()
countyNames2008 <- c()
stateNames2008 <- c() # Used to easily align states with counties and votes for the data frame

sapply(states, function(state) {
  if (state == "california" | state == "maine") {
    stateDF <- gs_read(gs_url(sourceURL2008), ws = capitalize(state), 
                      col_names = c("County", "Total Precincts", "Precincts Reporting", "Obama", "McCain", "Other"))
  } else {
    stateDF <- gs_read(gs_url(sourceURL2008), ws = capitalize(state))
  }
  countyNames2008 <<- tolower(c(countyNames2008, stateDF$County))
  demVoteCount2008 <<- c(demVoteCount2008, stateDF$Obama)
  repVoteCount2008 <<- c(repVoteCount2008, stateDF$McCain)
  otherCount2008 <<- c(otherCount2008, stateDF$Other)
  stateNames2008 <<- c(stateNames2008, rep(state, length(stateDF$County)))
})


perDemVotes2008 <- demVoteCount2008 / (demVoteCount2008 + otherCount2008 + repVoteCount2008)
perRepVotes2008 <- repVoteCount2008 / (demVoteCount2008 + otherCount2008 + repVoteCount2008)


countyNames2008 <- sub("( county)", "", countyNames2008)
countyNames2008 <- sub("(\\.)", "", countyNames2008)

countyNames2008 <- sub("&", "and", countyNames2008)
countyNames2008 <- sub("saint", "st", countyNames2008)

citiesToReplace2008 <- c("jodaviess", "debaca", "la vaca")

replaceWith2008 <- c("jo daviess", "de baca", "lavaca")

for (i in 1:length(citiesToReplace2008)){
  countyNames2008[grep(citiesToReplace2008[i], countyNames2008)] = replaceWith2008[i]
}


df2008 <- data.frame(countyNames2008, stateNames2008, demVoteCount2008, perDemVotes2008, repVoteCount2008, perRepVotes2008)

Step 1.6 - GML Extraction

Creates the vectors gmlStates, gmlCounties, gmlX, and gmlY to store geographic data of the counties. Extracts the state names in sequence and finds the size of each child. Formats gmlX and gmlY to become coordinates for latitude and longitude. Done by Allen

sourceURLgml <- "http://www.stat.berkeley.edu/~nolan/data/voteProject/counties.gml"
xmlValueTrim <- function(x) xmlValue(x, trim = TRUE)
gmlRoot <- xmlRoot(xmlParse(sourceURLgml))
gmlOrderedStates <- tolower(xpathSApply(gmlRoot, '//doc//state//gml:name[@abbreviation]', fun = xmlValueTrim))
numberTimeStateRepeated <- sapply(xmlChildren(gmlRoot), function(state) xmlSize(state) - 1) #First child is name, not county. Subtract one to account for first child)

gmlStates <- rep(gmlOrderedStates, numberTimeStateRepeated)
gmlCounties <- xpathSApply(gmlRoot, '//doc//state//gml:name[not(@abbreviation)]', fun = xmlValueTrim)
gmlX <- as.numeric(xpathSApply(gmlRoot, '//doc//state//gml:X', fun = xmlValueTrim))
gmlY <- as.numeric(xpathSApply(gmlRoot, '//doc//state//gml:Y', fun = xmlValueTrim))

gmlCounties <- tolower(gmlCounties) # Format county names
gmlCounties <- sub("( parish)|( county)", "", gmlCounties)
gmlCounties <- sub("(\\.)", "", gmlCounties)

for (i in 1:length(citiesToRemove)){
  gmlCounties[grep(citiesToRemove[i], gmlCounties)] = replaceWith[i]
}

latitude <- gmlY / 1000000
longitude <- gmlX / 1000000

gmlDF <- data.frame(gmlStates, gmlCounties ,latitude, longitude)

countyNames2016 <- tolower(sub("( Parish)|( County)", "", data2016$county_name))

Data Description

The data used in this project is from the 2004, 2008, 2012, and 2016 election. We also integrated demographic data from the 2010 census. For example, we have the percent of families living in poverty, the average household income, and educational attainment for each county. We were supplied this data in the form of text files, google forms, and csv files. In order to combine this data into a single data frame, the files had to be individually uploaded into the .rmd file, cleaned, and given columns to join on. After doing an initial cleaning for the four years of election data we calculated the winning party in each county - Republican, Democrat, or Other. In order to keep our data standardized, we removed the votes for “Other”, and only did an analysis of Republican vs. Democratic in our plots. In addition, the information for certain states/counties was excluded from specific data sets, so we ended up removing the information of those states/counties from all of the data sets (for the merge). For example, we do not include Alaska in our master data frame.

#Part 2- GGPlot

repVotes <- masterFrame$repVoteCount2012
demVotes <- masterFrame$demVoteCount2012

cond <- as.integer(repVotes < demVotes) + 1
#Scatter Plot 1

ssHouseholdAgeDF <- masterFrame[, c('dp02_HC03_VC18', 'dp03_HC03_VC90')]
ssHouseholdAgeDF['cond'] <- cond
ggplot(data = ssHouseholdAgeDF) + 
      geom_point(mapping = aes(x = dp02_HC03_VC18, y = dp03_HC03_VC90, color = factor(cond)), size = 1, position = "jitter", alpha = 0.35) +
      labs(title="Social Security vs. Household Age in 2012") +

      scale_x_continuous("Percentage: Families with 65 +") + 
      scale_y_continuous("Percentage: People with Social Security") + 
      scale_color_manual(name = "Counties: ", values = c("red", "blue"), labels = c("Rep", "Dem"))

Description - Strong positive correlation and linear association. A republican outlier where there’s about 60% of families with person 65+ and approximately 70% of people with Social Security. An important outlier is the red county at the approximate point of [62, 72]. This point is far separated from the cluster of points, and although it contains the same positive correlation as the other counties in the graph, the percentage in the x axis and the percentage in the y axis is extremely high. There are two explanations for this abnormality: this county could either be a rare occurrence of a county with limited youth and a majority of families without a stable income, or this county could be a data error.

For our national map, we wanted describe the 2016 results in the context of the 2012 election on a county-by-county basis. Originally, we decided to create a scatter plot with colors reflecting degree of slant in the republican or democratic decision and size representing the population of people. However, we found this initial plot hard to understand and not as effective in conveying the information that we wanted to get across. We then discovered the choroplethr package and reflected our data in terms of percentage shifts for county, which was effective in showing the general trends on the scale of the entire nation. We were able to notice a clear shift towards the republican candidate, Trump, in the midwest and a more general shift towards the democratic vote in the pacific northwest. We also noticed a clear general trend towards the red vote nationwide – the national average shifted ~3% towards Republican, as reflected in the scale.

We tried to capture the characteristics of this region in our parameters - namely education and jobs such as manufacturing.

electoral.votes <- purrr::map_chr(state.winprobs,
                                  function(winprob) {

                                  }) %>%

                             rvest::html_attr('data-card-id')
                         }) %>%
  stringr::str_extract('^..')
states <- tolower(states)

electoralVotesDF = data.frame(states, electoral.votes)

Step 5.1b, Naive Bayes Classification

Creates a naive bayes classifier for the result of a county (i.e. republican or democrat). After that, we use the distribution likelihood rather than the label to do weighted number of votes per county. For instance, since the classifer gives us the P(county votes democratic | census data), we calculate the expected number of democratic votes with county population * P(county votes democratic | census data). We them sum up the county votes in a state and which ever party has a simple majority, we allocate that number of electoral votes to it.

Cool features of e1071– Continuous variables use a normal distribution to calculate the probability. This means we don’t have to discretize time at all.

Done by Allen

# For debugging purposes
library(e1071)
load("ElectionsDataFrame.rda")

# Data must be numeric. ADD THIS FIX BEFORE TURNING IN DATA FRAME.
masterFrame$repVoteCount2012 = as.numeric(masterFrame$repVoteCount2012)

masterFrame$dp03_HC01_VC123 = as.numeric(masterFrame$dp03_HC01_VC123)
masterFrame$dp02_HC03_VC140 = as.numeric(masterFrame$dp02_HC03_VC140)

# Label based on 2012 winner
masterFrame$countyWinner2012 = masterFrame$demVoteCount2012 > masterFrame$repVoteCount2012
masterFrame$countyWinner2012 = factor(masterFrame$countyWinner2012, levels=c(FALSE,TRUE) ,labels=c("Rep", "Dem"))

# Getting rid of percentages, state names, counties, etc. Rationale is that count should be sufficient
columnsToRemove = c(seq(1, 8),10,12,14,16) * -1
testingData = split(masterFrame, masterFrame$stateAbbr)
stateAbbr = unique(masterFrame$stateAbbr)
countyPopulation = lapply(testingData, function(x) x[,"totalPopulation"]) # Indexed by state. Each element is a list of population per county
testingData = lapply(testingData, function(x) x[,columnsToRemove]) # We want this data to be refed to calculate the 2016 results.

trainingData = masterFrame[,columnsToRemove] # We want to calculate the posterior distribution with this data

model <- naiveBayes(countyWinner2012 ~ ., data = trainingData) # Generate the posterior distribution with Naive Bayes

# Calculates the probability distribution of voting Republican and Democrat. Predict is vectorized, so I can pass in an entire state
predictCountyDistribution = function(state) {
  predict(model, state, type="raw") 
}

votingLikelihood = lapply(testingData, predictCountyDistribution) #Indexed by state

# Calculating the expected votes for Republican and Democrat per state
expectedWinnerPerState = function(i) {
  distributionVector = as.vector(t(votingLikelihood[[i]]))
  countyPopulationVector = rep(countyPopulation[[i]], rep(2, length(countyPopulation[[i]])))
  expectedVotesByCounty = matrix(distributionVector * countyPopulationVector, ncol = 2, byrow = TRUE) # Left is Republican
  expectedPartyVotes = colSums(expectedVotesByCounty)
  if (expectedPartyVotes[1] > expectedPartyVotes[2]) {
    return("Republican Vote")
  } else {
    return("Democrat Vote")
  }
}
resultsColumn = factor(sapply(1:length(stateAbbr) , expectedWinnerPerState))
resultsDF = data.frame(stateAbbr, resultsColumn)

stateVotesResultDF = merge(resultsDF, electoralVotesDF, by.x="stateAbbr", by.y="states")
recast(stateVotesResultDF, resultsColumn ~ ., fun.aggregate=sum)

## 1   Democrat Vote 336
## 2 Republican Vote 191
# Calculating Error Rate of Counties

predictCountyResults = function(state) {
  predict(model, state)
}

masterFrame$countyWinner2016 = masterFrame$demVoteCount2016 > masterFrame$repVoteCount2016
masterFrame$countyWinner2016 = factor(masterFrame$countyWinner2016, levels=c(FALSE,TRUE) ,labels=c("Rep", "Dem"))
masterFrame$predictedWinner2016 = predictCountyResults(masterFrame)
errorRate = sum(masterFrame$countyWinner2016 != masterFrame$predictedWinner2016) / length(masterFrame$countyWinner2016)

Discussion

Classification Tree - Kim, Derrick, and Vinitra

We randomly selected 20% of the counties from each State to create testing and training data sets. We trained our data using the 2012 election results and tried to predict the 2016 election winner using different variables from the census data. We selected these variables based on our EDA above, choosing the 2012 Election results, the percentage of the county that has a graduate degree or professional degree, the percentage of the county whose highest educational attainment level was High School with no diploma, and the percentage of the county that works in manufacturing. We found that level of education was a pretty significant factor for predicting the election results, especially the percentage of the county with a graduate degree or other professional degree. We kept the size of the tree greater than 2 to also look at other factors. The effect of manufacturing was harder to examine. We then used a matrix to compare the predictions from the classification tree with the known results from the 2016 data – the values on the diagonal are correctly classified, so we have 500:57 correctly classified counties that voted Republican and 35:8 correctly classified counties that voted Democrat.

Naive Bayes Classifier - Allen & Shanaaz

We created a naive bayes classifier for the result of a county (i.e. Republican or Democrat). After that, we use the distribution likelihood rather than the label to do weighted number of votes per county. For instance, since the classifier gives us the P(county votes democratic | census data), we calculate the expected number of democratic votes with county population * P(county votes democratic | census data). We them sum up the county votes in a state and whichever party has a simple majority, we allocate that number of electoral votes to it. The error rate is 0.1101066.
